DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(81)80002-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426681800027
AB  - The ‘cost of capital” plays a key role in the allocation of funds between different sectors of the economy. The linkage between the cost of capital and market power has been hinted at by several authors. However, no rigorous development has been made. This paper uses the simple static analysis of the capital asset pricing model to show that with more market power a firm's cost of equity capital declines. Hence, firms with more market power will be able to raise equity capital at lower market rates than would the competitive firm, if the product market had been perfectly competitive.
ER  - 

